SIMPLE: spile
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spile
<hw>Spile</hw> <pr>(sp⟦imac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LG.
<ets>spile</ets>, dial. G. <ets>speil</ets>, <ets>speiler</ets>, D.
<ets>spijl</ets>. ⟦root⟧170.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small plug or
wooden pin, used to stop a vent, as in a cask.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1386 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small tube or spout inserted in a tree for
conducting sap, as from a sugar maple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A large stake driven into the ground as a support
for some superstructure; a pile.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>One of the thick laths or poles
driven horizontally ahead on top of a set of the main timbering in
advancing a level in loose ground.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> forepole; spill{2d}.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>RDH</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spile hole</b></col>, <cd>a small air hole in a cask; a
vent.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spile
<hw>Spile</hw> <pr>(sp⟦imac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To supply
with a spile or a spigot; to make a small vent in, as a cask.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spilikin</ent>⟦br⟧
